Let&#x27;s extend your program to make it even more interesting:<p><pre><code>  #include <math.h>
  #include <string.h>
  #include <stdio.h>

  int main()
  {
      float x = NAN;
      float y = NAN;

      printf(&quot;x == y is %d
&quot;, (x == y) ? 1 : 0);
      printf(&quot;memcmp(&x, &y, ...) is %d
&quot;,
	     memcmp(&x, &y, sizeof x));
      return 0;
  }
</code></pre>
Output:<p><pre><code>  x == y is 0
  memcmp(&x, &y, ...) is 0
</code></pre>
memcmp says they are the same bit pattern.<p>In fact, even x == x will fail.  Direct violation of &quot;A is A&quot;.<p>> NAN is similar concept to NULL in databases<p>But not similar in concept to NULL in C, where NULL == NULL.
